olence and insecurity that poses serious threats to democratic transition and rule of law. This is the first book to put these developments in the context of post-revolutionary state-making in Mexico and to show that violence in Mexico is not the result of state failure, but of state-making. While most accounts of politics and the state in recent decades have emphasized processes of transition, institutional conflict resolution, and neo-liberal reform, this volume lays out the increasingly important role of violence and coercion by a range of state and non-state armed actors. Moreover, by going beyond the immediate concerns of contemporary Mexico, this volume pushes us to rethink longterm processes of state-making and recast influential interpretations of the so-called golden years of PRI rule. Violence, Coercion, and State-Making in Twentieth-Century Mexico demonstrates that received wisdom has long prevented the concerted and systematic study of violence and coercion in state-making, not only during the last decades, but throughout the post-revolutionary period. The Mexican state was built much more on violence and coercion than has been acknowledged-until now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aViolencexPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxMexico. 0aViolencexPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th centuryxMexico. 0aViolencexPolitical aspectszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Freedom.2bisacsh1 aShirk, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Diane E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBortz, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGledhill, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAguiar, José Carlos G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id